      {
        "title": "Formal requests with 'May I...?'",
        "explanation": "The phrase 'May I...?' is a polite and formal way to ask for permission or make a request. 'May' in this context means 'to be allowed to'."
      },
      {
        "title": "Expression: 'It's worth every penny of it.'",
        "explanation": "This idiom emphasizes that something is of very good value and worth the money or effort spent on it. 'It' refers to the item or service being discussed."
      },
      {
        "title": "Usage of 'yet' in negative sentences",
        "explanation": "'Yet' is often used in negative sentences and questions in the present perfect tense to mean 'up to now' or 'so far'. It indicates that an action has not happened by a certain time, but is expected to happen."
      },
      {
        "title": "Modal verb 'must' for obligation",
        "explanation": "'Must' is a modal verb used to express strong obligation, necessity, or certainty. It indicates that something is essential or required."
      },
      {
        "title": "Present Perfect Tense with 'yet'",
        "explanation": "The present perfect tense (have/has + past participle) is used to describe actions that happened at an unspecified time before now, or actions that started in the past and continue to the present. When combined with 'yet' in questions or negative statements, it asks if something has happened up to the present moment or states that it hasn't."
      },
      {
        "title": "Irregular Verbs (Past Participle Forms)",
        "explanation": "Many English verbs have irregular past tense and past participle forms. It is important to memorize these forms, especially the past participle, as they are crucial for forming the present perfect tense and passive voice."
      }
